Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Todd Gillespie, Gavin Finch, Will Mathis and Jason=
 Grotto have a story about  UK electric producer Drax Group Plc=E2=80=99s g=
reen energy subsidies:

Since December 2016, a generator at the firm=E2=80=99s giant power plant ha=
d received =C2=A31.4 billion ($1.8 billion) in green-energy subsidies from =
consumers =E2=80=94 payments above the market rate for electricity. The goa=
l of this public aid was to make it profitable for Drax to fuel the unit wi=
th =E2=80=9Cbiomass,=E2=80=9D pellets made from wood that are considered a =
renewable energy source.
This expensive method for weaning Britain=E2=80=99s power grid off fossil f=
uels contained a consumer safeguard: If electricity prices ever increased e=
nough that Drax=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CUnit 1=E2=80=9D generator could comforta=
bly make money without subsidies, its earnings would be capped, and the com=
pany would have to send any extra cash back to bill payers.

Here is specifically how the subsidy works:

This particular opportunity stemmed from a type of subsidy agreement called=
 =E2=80=9Ccontracts for difference,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CCfDs=E2=80=9D for =
short. The CfD for Drax=E2=80=99s Unit 1 follows a straightforward logic.
First, negotiators agree on how much it will cost Drax to produce electrici=
ty from biomass. They add some extra to ensure a reasonable profit. This to=
tal is called the =E2=80=9Cstrike price.=E2=80=9D
Then they figure out how much the firm can sell its electricity for on the =
wholesale market. If that =E2=80=9Cmarket reference price=E2=80=9D is lower=
 than the strike price, consumers have to send Drax the rest of the money =
=E2=80=94 the =E2=80=9Cdifference=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 via charges added to t=
heir energy bills.
But if the market reference price rises above the strike price, the arrange=
ment flips. The contract holds that Drax, now assured of turning a profit, =
must send the difference back to energy suppliers, who by law then reduce w=
hat they charge consumers.

Ah! If the market price is below $20, they get paid $20.
  [1]
=C2=A0If the market price is above $20, they get paid $20. How much should =
they sell if the market price is below $20? As much as they can. How much s=
